article.description: The host Charlotte Sting, last in the WNBA in scoring, converted 20 Minnesota turnovers into 29 points in a 66-58 victory over the Lynx on Thursday night.
article.headline: Lynx's Smith near 5,000-point mark in loss
article.linkText: Lynx stung, fall back to .500 club
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- With their offense in a funk, the
Charlotte Sting turned up the defense to snap a three-game losing
streak.

The Sting, last in the WNBA in scoring, converted 20 Minnesota
turnovers into 29 points in a 66-58 victory over the Lynx on
Thursday night.

"Our strength is in our defense," Charlotte coach Trudi Lacey
said. "That's how we have to beat people, with our team defense
and our team offense. They're committed to that."

Allison Feaster scored 19 points, including five 3-pointers, to
lead Charlotte. Tangela Smith had 15 points and Tammy Sutton-Brown
added 13.

The Sting set a season high in steals with 14 while winning for
just the third time.

"We did a tremendous defensive job on a very talented Minnesota
team," Feaster said.

Katie Smith scored 12 for the Lynx and needs 11 points to become
the first woman to score 5,000 points in her professional career in
the United States. She scored 1,431 points during two-plus seasons
in the ABL and has 3,558 with Minnesota.

Vanessa Hayden led Minnesota with 13 points and 10 rebounds,
while reserve Tamika Williams added 10 points.

Charlotte took control of the game in the second half by forcing
five consecutive Lynx turnovers during a 10-0 run to take a 53-37
lead with 13 minutes remaining.

"They scored 29 points off turnovers. That was the
difference," Minnesota coach Suzie McConnell Serio said. "I will
be watching a lot of game film during the All-Star break.
Offensively, it was very ugly tonight."

The Lynx head into the All-Star weekend with a two-game losing
streak.

"They got some deflections, had some great individual effort
and they rotated well," Katie Smith said. "They're long and
active. They got some steals and were able to go in and get some
scores."

Smith scored 10 points in the first half, but took only a single
3-pointer in the second.

"I think I took one shot or something, I don't know," Smith
said. "Nothing. I sat for a little while. I don't think I was in
the ball game much."

Lacey credited Feaster for putting the defensive clamps on
Smith.

"She played 39 minutes and guarded one of the most prolific
scorers in WNBA history," Lacey said. "She does that night in and
night out."

Feaster shrugged off the praise.

"I can't even take credit for that," Feaster said. "She's an
awesome offensive player, she reads screens so well. My teammates
did a great job in helping me out, switching out on her when I was
beaten."

Charlotte's Jia Perkins scored seven consecutive points, and
Dawn Staley and Feaster each converted steals into easy layups to
complete the decisive 10-0 run in the second half.

The 53-37 lead was the largest enjoyed by the Sting this season.
Minnesota responded with nine unanswered points -- three inside
baskets by Tamika Williams and a 3-pointer by Amanda Lassiter -- to
trim Charlotte's lead to 53-46.

Tangela Smith then helped the Sting put the game away by scoring
seven of her team's next 10 points to push Charlotte to a 63-50
edge with 5:28 remaining.

Charlotte led by as many as 11 in the first half, using an
inside-outside game to grab a 32-21 lead with about 5 minutes left
in the half. Feaster nailed two 3-pointers, while Sutton-Brown
scored two inside baskets during a 13-4 run.

The Sting's Sheri Sam reached the 2,500-point mark with a layup
early in the game. Sam, a six-year veteran, became the 21st player
in league history to reach the milestone.
